There's still a problem - name_from_children and tag_graph_build still call cvm_file_read for uncached DLL children of #TAG. When name_from_children tries kids of a DLL token, it might fetch the name ...The white screen is happening because `name_prefix_find` (which is called every frame by the HUD match path) unconditionally calls `name_load()` even when the query is empty. That triggers `tag_graph_build` on the first frame, which then starts downloading DLLs via `cvm_file_read` because the graph still has uncached children.

The core issue is that `name_prefix_find` should only call `name_load` once the query is non-empty. Right now it always does:

```c
name_load();
if (q && q[0]) {
    // only then do the real lookup
}
```

So the 64-DLL download happens on frame 1.

Fix is simple: move the `name_load()` inside the `if (q && q[0])` block. That stops the graph from being built on startup.

Additionally, harden `tag_graph_build` so it never fetches a node itself if `name_from_children 0` and it's a DLL (self-loop or no name child). For tags like `#editor`, the small content fetch is fine once we skip the DLLs.

Do the `name_load` guard first — that should kill the white screen immediately. Then we can tighten the child-fetch logic if we still see DLL spam 10 seconds later. Want me to give you the exact patch for `name_prefix_find`? Or shall we look at the `name_from_children` disk-only change next? Either way, the hang is fixed by that one line. Let me know which direction you want to go.

